<item>
            <title>[SPARK-32663] TransportClient getting closed when there are outstanding requests to the server</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/SPARK-32663</link>
                <project id="12315420" key="SPARK">Spark</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;The implementation of &lt;tt&gt;removeBlocks&lt;/tt&gt; and &lt;tt&gt;getHostLocalDirs&lt;/tt&gt; in &lt;tt&gt;ExternalBlockStoreClient&lt;/tt&gt; closes the client after processing a response in the callback. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This is a cached client which will be re-used for other responses. There could be other outstanding request to the shuffle service, so it should not be closed after processing a response. &lt;br/&gt;
Seems like this is a bug introduced with &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/SPARK-27651&quot; title=&quot;Avoid the network when block manager fetches shuffle blocks from the same host&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;SPARK-27651&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;SPARK-27651&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/SPARK-27677&quot; title=&quot;Disk-persisted RDD blocks served by shuffle service, and ignored for Dynamic Allocation&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;SPARK-27677&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;SPARK-27677&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The older methods  &lt;tt&gt;registerWithShuffleServer&lt;/tt&gt; and &lt;tt&gt;fetchBlocks&lt;/tt&gt; didn&apos;t close the client.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;cc &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=attilapiros&quot; class=&quot;user-hover&quot; rel=&quot;attilapiros&quot;&gt;attilapiros&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=vanzin&quot; class=&quot;user-hover&quot; rel=&quot;vanzin&quot;&gt;vanzin&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=mridulm80&quot; class=&quot;user-hover&quot; rel=&quot;mridulm80&quot;&gt;mridulm80&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
